04284nam a22005655i 9780226237015DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014027724  a9780226237015  a(DE-B1597)525035  a(OCoLC)904598369  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHD69.S8bS674 2015 4aHD69.S8bS674 2017 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a302.352231 aSpinuzzi, Clay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAll Edge :bInside the New Workplace Networks /cClay Spinuzzi. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b14 halftones, 9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Becoming All Edge -- t2. What Are All- Edge Adhocracies? -- t3. Stage Management: The Case of Nonemployer Firms -- t4. The Foundation of All- Edge Adhocracies: Organizational Networks -- t5. Working Alone, Together: The Case of Coworking -- t6. The Dynamic Structure of All- Edge Adhocracies: Activities -- t7. Lone Wolves: The Case of Search Engine Optimization -- t8. The Confi gurations of All- Edge Adhocracies: Hierarchies, Markets, Clans, and Networks -- t9. The Work of All- Edge Adhocracies: The Three Integrations -- t10. The Future of All- Edge Adhocracies -- tAppendix: Methodology -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWork is changing. Speed and flexibility are more in demand than ever before thanks to an accelerating knowledge economy and sophisticated communication networks. These changes have forced a mass rethinking of the way we coordinate, collaborate, and communicate. Instead of projects coming to established teams, teams are increasingly converging around projects. These “all-edge adhocracies” are highly collaborative and mostly temporary, their edge coming from the ability to form links both inside and outside an organization. These nimble groups come together around a specific task, recruiting personnel, assigning roles, and establishing objectives. When the work is done they disband their members and take their skills to the next project. Spinuzzi offers for the first time a comprehensive framework for understanding how these new groups function and thrive. His rigorous analysis tackles both the pros and cons of this evolving workflow and is based in case studies of real all-edge adhocracies at work. His provocative results will challenge our long-held assumptions about how we should be doing work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBusiness communication. 0aBusiness enterprisesxTechnological innovations. 0aBusiness networks. 0aKnowledge economy. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aworkplace, work, networks, rhetoric, rhetorical, writing, working, knowledge economy, communication network, coordination, collaboration, communicating, organization, recruitment, objectives, business, technology, technological, innovation, adhocracies, management, coworking, search engine optimization, hierarchy, integration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022623696440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226237015423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226237015/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles